3 Variables

Here is the information regarding different variables found in the dataset.

Useful definitions:

gill - papery rib under the cap of some mushroom species. Gills are used by the mushroom as a means of spore dispersal.

bruise - discoloring due to damage.

stalk - stem of a mushroom, supports the cap.

veil - protective layer for a mushroom when it grows out of the ground. When the mushroom matures it pushes through the veil and part of it is left at the bottom of the stalk.

ring - remnant of the veil,forms around the stalk.

spore print - the result of capturing spores in a very uniform way onto a piece of paper or other material

3.1 class

Defines edibility of a mushroom. 2 possible values:

  • e = edible
  • p = poisonous or of unknown edibility

4 What makes mushrooms edible?

In this section, I want to determine what are the distinctive characteristics of an edible or inedible mushrooms. Edible mushrooms are marked in green whereas poisonous mushrooms are marked in red.

Looking at the plots, it seems we can be most convinced of the mushroomâ€™s edibility when we are able verify its odor or spore-print-color, because depending on those two variables, the mushroom is almost certainly edible or poisonous.

Based on the data we can be sure that a mushroom is edible when it has one of the following characteristics:
